      <abstract>
        <p>Reynold Weidenaar letter says airline passengers are captive audiences not only to flight-crew entertainment (Feb 17 article), but also to corporate promotion masquerading as safety information</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Captive Audience 30,000 Feet in the Air'' (On the Road column, Business Day, Feb. 17):</p>
        <p>Air travelers are captive audiences not only to flight-crew entertainment but also to corporate promotion masquerading as safety information.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Captive Audience 30,000 Feet in the Air'' (On the Road column, Business Day, Feb. 17):</p>
        <p>Air travelers are captive audiences not only to flight-crew entertainment but also to corporate promotion masquerading as safety information.</p>
        <p>On a recent United Air Lines flight, the instructional videos were slathered with pumped-up iconic theme music, logos, slick graphics and glorious shots of sun rays and clouds.</p>
        <p>We used to see live flight attendants demonstrating the operation of real oxygen masks and seat belts. Now we see the apparatus on camera in the hands of smile-crazed models who are so buff and beautiful they could pass for television news anchors.</p>
        <p>The subtext speaks chiefly to corporate image and very little to safety.</p>
        <p>REYNOLD WEIDENAAR  New York, Feb. 17, 2004</p>
      </block>
